{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637625"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:44:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:44:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17674"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17674"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.05,0.05,0.29,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71980"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7592"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24309"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71980"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the proximal tubule of the kidney, glucose is reabsorbed from the filtrate back into the blood through a two-step process. The second step involves movement across the basolateral membrane.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of glucose transport across the basolateral membrane of proximal tubular cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Secondary active transport with sodium","Paracellular diffusion between cells","Simple diffusion through lipid bilayer","Facilitated diffusion down concentration gradient","Active transport against concentration gradient"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism is \u003Cstrong\u003Efacilitated diffusion down concentration gradient\u003C/strong\u003E. After glucose is actively transported into proximal tubular cells at the apical membrane via sodium-glucose cotransporters, it moves across the basolateral membrane through GLUT transporters. This process does not require energy as glucose moves down its concentration gradient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary active transport with sodium\u003C/strong\u003E is only required at the apical membrane where glucose moves against its concentration gradient. At the basolateral membrane, sodium coupling is unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacellular diffusion between cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; glucose transport occurs through specific membrane proteins within the cell membrane rather than between cells via the paracellular pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDue to its size and polarity, glucose cannot undergo \u003Cstrong\u003Esimple diffusion through the membrane lipid bilayer\u003C/strong\u003E and instead requires specific transport proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe energy-requiring process of \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive transport against concentration gradient\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary since glucose is moving down its concentration gradient at the basolateral membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFacilitated diffusion exhibits saturation kinetics, meaning the rate of transport reaches a maximum when all available transport proteins are occupied. This is characteristic of carrier-mediated transport.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Facilitated diffusion uses specific transport proteins to move molecules down their concentration gradient without requiring energy.","Glucose reabsorption in the proximal tubule occurs via facilitated diffusion through GLUT transporters.","The rate of facilitated diffusion reaches a maximum when all transport proteins are occupied (saturation kinetics)."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17674"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T20:53:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T20:54:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71980"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"h